<DOC><DOCNO> AP881007-0115 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-10-07-88 1231EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Finland-Politics     10-07 0140</FIRST><SECOND>AM-BRF--Finland-Politics,0145</SECOND><HEAD>Governing Coalition Survives No-Confidence Motion</HEAD><DATELINE>HELSINKI, Finland (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The four-party governing coalitionFriday survived its fourth motion of no-confidence since takingoffice 17 months ago.   Conservative Prime Minister Harri Holkeri's government, whichincludes the Social Democrats, the Rural Party and the SwedishPeople's Party, won the vote 123-64, with 12 members absent.   The motion criticized the government's tax reform plans and the1989 budget proposals, which the opposition said favored the rich.   The main opposition Center Party, which has been gaining supportin opinion polls since the last election, charges the governmenthas not done enough for students and the poor.   A survey published last month indicated growing disillusionmentwith the government.   The survey showed that the Conservatives and the SocialDemocrats had only 40 percent support, down from 47 percent in theMarch 1987 election.</TEXT></DOC>